{"id":"project-LICHEN-xp70","title":"Role pointer in app_status_snapshot may dangle after callback returns","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/app_interface/include/lichen/app_interface/app_interface.h:178-186

  struct lichen_app_status_snapshot {
      uint16_t rank;
      uint32_t uptime_seconds;
      const char *role;  // <-- pointer, not array
      bool rpl_capable;
      ...
  };

The role field is a raw pointer, not a fixed-size buffer like source_name[24] in other structs.

In lichen_app_interface_get_status() (app_interface.c:372-401):
  memset(status, 0, sizeof(*status));
  ret = snapshot[i].get_status(status, snapshot[i].user_data);
  if (ret == 0) {
      return 0;  // returns with status->role pointing to sink's memory
  }

If the sink's get_status callback sets role to point to its own internal memory (stack or heap):
1. Caller receives status with role pointer
2. If sink is unregistered or its memory freed, role becomes a dangling pointer
3. Caller dereferencing role triggers undefined behavior

Unlike source_name[24] which copies data, role just stores a pointer with no lifetime guarantee.

Fix: Either:
1. Change role to char role[N] array with strncpy
2. Document that role must point to static/long-lived memory
